  "prompt": "Why do people with white skin get burnt easily?",
  "response": "People with lighter skin, particularly those with white or very fair skin, tend to burn more easily due to several factors related to skin pigmentation and the way the skin responds to ultraviolet (UV) radiation from the sun.\n\n1. **Melanin Levels**: Melanin is the pigment that gives skin its color and provides some protection against UV radiation. People with lighter skin have less melanin compared to those with darker skin. This lower concentration of melanin means that there is less natural protection against UV rays, making their skin more susceptible to sunburn.\n\n2. **Skin Type**: The Fitzpatrick scale classifies skin types based on their response to UV exposure. Individuals with lighter skin (types I and II) are more likely to burn rather than tan when exposed to sunlight. This is in contrast to those with darker skin who can better tolerate sun exposure and may tan instead of burning.\n\n3. **UV Radiation**: UV rays are harmful and can cause skin damage. Light-skinned individuals may not have sufficient protective mechanisms, making them more prone to sunburn, which is an inflammatory response to the damage caused by UV radiation.\n\n4. **Accumulated Damage**: Repeated exposure to UV light without adequate protection can lead to cumulative skin damage in lighter-skinned individuals, making them more likely to experience burns over time.\n\nTo protect against sunburn, it is advisable for individuals with lighter skin to use sunscreen with a high SPF, wear protective clothing, and seek shade during peak sun hours.",
